Níṣókí 
Wọ́n mú àkọ́lé lati Ovid. 
Ó sàfihàn ọlọ́dẹ Adonis tí ó sùn sí orí itan Venus. 
Eros wà níwájú ẹ̀ pẹ̀lú ajá ọdẹ kan. 
Wọ́n ṣe àfihàn Cupid níbi tí ó ti ń gbìyànjú lati má jẹ́ kí ajá yìí dẹgbó nítorí pé Venus ti sàsọtẹ́lẹ̀ wípé Adonis ma ́a kú ní àkókò ọdẹ. 
Àlà ilẹ̀ wà ní abẹ́lẹ̀ pẹ́lú àwọ̀ ewé àti ojú ọ̀run tó búlúù. 
Tún wòó 
Àwọ́n ìtọ́kasí 
Professor Moshood Abiola Peller (Odun 1941, Iseyin – Ọjọ́ kejì Oṣù kẹjọ Ọdún 1997, Onipanu) jẹ́ onídán ọmọ orílẹ̀ èdè Nàìjíríà tí ó jẹ́ ìkan lára àwọn ògbónta onídán ti Áfíríkà.[1][2][3] 
Àwọn ìtọ́kasí 
Ìbẹ́pẹ (/pəˈpaɪə/ or US /pəˈpɑːjə/) (from Carib via Spanish), papaw, (/pəˈpɔː/[2]) or pawpaw (/ˈpɔːˌpɔː/[2]) jẹ́ èso irúgbìn Carica papaya, tí ó sì jẹ́ méjìlélógún àwọn ẹ̀yà ìdílé Carica ti ẹbí irúgbin Caricaceae.[3] 
Biochemistry, nígbàmíràn wọ́n máa ń pèé ní biological chemistry, jẹ́ ìmọ̀ ìlànà kẹ́míkà àgọ́ ara àtí ìbáṣepọ̀ wọn pẹ̀lú ohun ẹlẹmí.[1] Nípa ṣíṣe àkóso lílọ-bíbọ̀ iṣẹ́ lágọ́ ara nípasẹ̀ ìtalólobo ìbáṣepọ̀ kẹ́míkà àti lílọ-bíbọ̀ agbára kẹ́míkà làtàrí gbogbo ìbáṣepọ̀ kẹ́míka nínú ara, ìlànà kẹ́míkà nínú ara yìí ní ó máa ń ṣe ìmúgbòòrò bí ara ṣe ń ṣiṣẹ́. Ní bíi ogún ọrundún sẹ́yìn, biochemistry ti ṣe àṣeyọrí lórí bí a ṣe lè ṣàlàyé lórí ìlànà ìgbéayé tí ó ni ṣe pẹ̀lú ìmọ ohun ẹlẹ́mí làti ìmọ̀ ewéko sí ìmọ̀ ìlera, sí ìmọ̀ ìṣiṣẹ́àbínimọ́ ní wọ́n ní ṣe pẹ̀lú ìwádí ìbáṣepọ̀ kẹ́míkà lágọ́ ara.[2] Loní, ìdojúkọ ìwádí ní biochemistry dá lórí òye bí biological molecules ṣe ń f ìlànà tó ń ṣẹlẹ̀ nínú àwọn ètò ẹ̀yà ara. By controlling information flow through biochemical signaling and the flow of chemical energy through metabolism, biochemical processes give rise to the complexity of life. 
Len Deighton (bíi Ọjọ́ kejídínlógún Oṣù kejí ọdún 1929) jẹ́ olùkọ̀tàn gẹ̀ẹ́sì tí wọ́n mọ̀ sí àwọn ìwé àkàkọ́gbọ́n, àwọn iṣẹ́ ìtàn ológun, ìfàwòránsọ̀tàn àtí kíkọ nípa bí a ṣe ń se oúnjẹ́. 
Ó ní oríṣiriṣi iṣẹ́, iṣẹ́ rẹ̀ pẹ̀lú àkàra díndín, agbáwo oúnjẹ, ara àwọn olùkọ̀wé ìròyín, olùkọ́ àti ara àwọn to ń ṣiṣẹ́ nínú ọkọ̀ òfurufú kí ó tó kọ àkọ́kọ́ ìwé àkàkọ́gbọ́n rẹ̀ ní ọdún 1962: The IPCRESS File.[1][2] Ó ń tẹ̀síwájú ṣe o oun tí olùkọ̀tàn ìgbésíayérẹ̀ pè ní "oge, àwàdà, ìwé àkàkọ́gbọ́n tó dára ní ìtan ọfintótó,[3] pẹ̀lú àwọn ìwé àkàkọ́gbọ́n kí ó to ṣàfihàn Bernard Samson.[4][lower-alpha 1] 
Oríṣiríṣi 
Ọ̀pọ̀lọpọ̀ iṣẹ́ Deighton ni wọ́n ti fi ṣe eré: Eré The Ipcress File (1965),[12] Funeral in Berlin (1966),[13] Billion Dollar Brain (1967)[14] àti Spy Film (1976).[15] Ní ọdún 1988 amóùnmáwòran Granada ṣàgbéjáde miniseries Game, Set and Match tí ó dálórí àwọn ìwé àkàkọ́gbọ́n rẹ̀ mẹ́ta tí ó ń jẹ́ orúkọ kan náà.[16] 
Àwọn oríṣiríṣi iṣẹ́ Deighton Àkọ́lé[17][18] Ọdún tí wọ́n kọ́kọ́ gbe jáde Alágéjáde àkọ́kọ́ (Gbogbo rẹ̀ ní London àfi ti wọ́n bá ní kò ríbẹ́ẹ̀ Notes Long Past Glory 1963.1 ! 1963 – Television script[19] Len Deighton's Cookstrips 1963.2 ! 1963 sí 1965 Observer !The Observer Weekly cookery strip[20][21] Drinkmanship 1964 Haymarket Press As editor Oh! 
What a Lovely War 1969 – Film script; Deighton requested that he not be given screen credit for his work.[22] Declarations of War 1971 Jonathan Cape Short stories How to be a Pregnant Father 1977.1 !1977 Macmillan Publishers Book by Peter Mayle; Deighton provided the chapter "The Pregnant Father's Cookbook" It Must Have Been Two Other Fellows 1977.2 !1977 – Television script[3] Tactical Genius in Battle 1979 Phaidon Press Book by Simon Goodenough; Deighton acted as editor and provided the introduction Adventure of the Priory School !The Adventure of the Priory School 1985 ! 1985 Santa Teresa Press, Santa Barbara, CA Introduction only; original work by Arthur Conan Doyle. 
